    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The zero set should locally be a subvariety (of positive codimension) and I don't think you can really go beyond that.</p>",
        "id": 469002639,
        "sender_full_name": "S√©bastien Gou√´zel",
        "timestamp": 1725951739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I apologize, I don't know algebraic geometry, could you clarify?</p>",
        "id": 469003306,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1725951959
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In dimension 2, the zero set should be a union of curves and points.</p>",
        "id": 469003813,
        "sender_full_name": "S√©bastien Gou√´zel",
        "timestamp": 1725952091
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The principle of isolated zeroes requires not only connectedness but also irreducibility: the set should not be the union of two smaller analytic subsets.<br>\nFor the probably simplest possible example, in 2 variables, take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>w</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> f(z,w)=z </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span></span></span></span> on the set defined by the equation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>z</mi><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> zw=0 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 469013326,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725953849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In dimension 1 you might be looking for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=AnalyticOn.eqOn_zero_of_preconnected_of_frequently_eq_zero#doc\">docs#AnalyticOn.eqOn_zero_of_preconnected_of_frequently_eq_zero</a> (plus some glue saying that a connected set that is not a point has no isolated point so <code>f =·∂†[ùìù[U] z‚ÇÄ] 0</code> implies that it is frequently zero)</p>",
        "id": 469098314,
        "sender_full_name": "Vincent Beffara",
        "timestamp": 1725976325
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That glue is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsPreconnected.preperfect_of_nontrivial#doc\">docs#IsPreconnected.preperfect_of_nontrivial</a>, right? I want to add the result that an analytic function which is frequently zero along codiscreteWithin is zero everywhere, so I'm trying to figure out the right generality. Is it simply one dimension?</p>",
